---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<!-- Testing GitHub Actions deployment -->
<Layout title="Email Export Tool">
	<main>
		<img src="/email-export-tool-icon.png" alt="Email Export Tool" class="stamp" width="640" height="682" />
		<h1>Email Export Tool</h1>
		<p class="tagline">Turn your beautiful Canva email designs into emails that work perfectly in any email client.</p>

		<section class="problem">
			<h2>The Problem</h2>
			<p>
				You've spent time creating a gorgeous email design in Canva. You export it, open the file, and it looks perfect
				on your computer. But the moment you try to send it as an email or paste it into your email client, all your images disappear
				or show up as broken image icons. Your carefully crafted design is ruined.
			</p>
			<p>
				Here's why: when Canva exports your design, it creates a file that references images saved on your computer —
				like when a Word document has a photo stored in your "Documents" folder. This works fine when you're viewing it locally,
				but email clients can't reach into your computer to grab those images. They need the
				images to be hosted online, on the internet, where anyone can access them.
			</p>
		</section>

		<section class="solution">
			<h2>How We Fix It</h2>
			<p>
				Email Export Tool does the technical work for you. When you upload your Canva export (either as a folder or a ZIP file),
				we automatically take all your images and upload them to a professional image hosting service. Then we update your email
				design so it points to these new, web-accessible image locations instead of files on your computer.
			</p>
			<p>
				The result? You get back an email-ready version of your design that you can copy and paste directly into any email client,
				and all your images will display perfectly for everyone who receives it. No technical knowledge
				required, no manual uploading, no broken images.
			</p>
		</section>
	</main>
</Layout>

<style>
	main {
		max-width: var(--width-content);
		margin: 0 auto;
		padding: var(--space-16) var(--space-4);
		text-align: center;
	}

	.stamp {
		width: 120px;
		height: auto;
		margin-bottom: var(--space-8);
		display: block;
		margin-left: auto;
		margin-right: auto;
	}

	h1 {
		font-size: var(--text-4xl);
		margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
	}

	.tagline {
		font-size: var(--text-lg);
		color: var(--color-text-muted);
		line-height: 1.6;
		max-width: 40rem;
		margin: 0 auto var(--space-16);
	}

	section {
		max-width: 48rem;
		margin: 0 auto var(--space-12);
		padding: var(--space-8);
		background: var(--color-bg);
		border-radius: 0.5rem;
		text-align: left;
	}

	section h2 {
		font-size: var(--text-2xl);
		margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
		color: var(--color-primary);
	}

	section p {
		font-size: var(--text-base);
		line-height: 1.8;
		margin-bottom: var(--space-4);
		color: var(--color-text);
	}

	section p:last-child {
		margin-bottom: 0;
	}
</style>
